EasyVisa Project¶

Project Overview and Objective¶

Context:

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective:

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired your firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

  • Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
  • Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of the employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full Time Position; N = Part Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

def print_outliers_info(data, feature):
   """
   Calculates upper outlier analysis information to pair with visualizations

   data: dataframe
   feature: dataframe column
   """
   Q1 = data[feature].quantile(0.25)
   Q3 = data[feature].quantile(0.75)
   IQR = Q3 - Q1
   upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
   max_feat = data[feature].max()

   outliers = data[(data[feature] > upper_bound)][feature].unique()
   outliers_sorted = np.sort(outliers)

   if len(outliers_sorted) > 6:
       outliers_sorted_abbr = np.append(outliers_sorted[:6], "...etc")
   else:
       outliers_sorted_abbr = outliers_sorted

   if len(outliers) > 0:
       outlier_df = pd.DataFrame({
           "IQR": [IQR],
           "Q3": [Q3],
           "Upper Bound": [upper_bound],
           "Max" : [max_feat],
           "#rows > Upper Bound": [len(data[data[feature] > upper_bound])]
       })
       print(f"{feature} Outliers Information:\n")
       formatted_df = outlier_df.to_string(index=False, col_space=15, justify='left') + '\n'
       print(formatted_df)
       print(f"Unique Values Above Upper Bound: {outliers_sorted_abbr}")

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(15, 10), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """

    # creating the 2 subplots
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,
        sharex=True,
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75), "hspace": 0.05, "top": 0.95},
        figsize=figsize,
    )

    # create a title
    f2.suptitle(f"Histogram and Boxplot for {feature}", fontsize=16)

    # boxplot will be created and a square will indicate the mean value of the column
    create_boxplot(data, feature, ax_box2)

    # create histogram, with consideration of bins
    create_histogram(data, feature, ax_hist2, kde, bins)

    # Calculate and print outliers information for the specific feature
    print_outliers_info(data, feature)

def create_boxplot(data, feature, ax_box):
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        ax=ax_box,
        showmeans=True,
        meanprops={"marker": "s", "markersize": 8, "markerfacecolor": custom_palette[1], "markeredgecolor": "black"},
        medianprops={'linewidth': 4},
        color=custom_palette[2]
    )
    ax_box.set_xlabel("")

def create_histogram(data, feature, ax_hist, kde, bins):
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist, bins=bins, alpha=0.7
    ) if bins is not None else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist, alpha=0.7
    )
    add_mean_median_to_histogram(data, feature, ax_hist)

def add_mean_median_to_histogram(data, feature, ax_hist):
    ax_hist.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=8
    )
    ax_hist.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color=custom_palette[1], linestyle='-', linewidth=5, label="Mean"
    )
    ax_hist.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color='black', linestyle='-', linewidth=5, label="Median"
    )
    ax_hist.legend(loc='upper right')

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None, rotation=90, sort_index=False):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    sort_index: whether to sort the index (default is False)
    """
    # Check data type of the column
    if data[feature].dtype == 'O':
       print(f"Skipping outlier analysis for {feature} as it contains string values.")
    elif np.issubdtype(data[feature].dtype, np.number):  # Check if dtype is numeric
       # Perform some action for numeric dtype
       print(f"Performing numeric-specific action for {feature}")
       # Calculate and print outliers information for the specific feature
       print_outliers_info(data, feature)
    else:
       print(f"Unsupported dtype for {feature}.")

    # Plot the barplot
    plot_barplot(data, feature, perc, n, rotation, sort_index)

def plot_barplot(data, feature, perc, n, rotation, sort_index):
    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation, fontsize=15)

    order = data[feature].value_counts().index[:n]
    if sort_index:
        order = sorted(order)

    ax = create_countplot(data, feature, order)

    for p in ax.patches:
        add_percentage_label(p, total, perc)

    # Add title
    plt.title(f"Barplot for {feature}")

    plt.show()  # show the plot

def create_countplot(data, feature, order):
    return sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette=custom_palette,
        order=order,
    )

def add_percentage_label(p, total, perc):
    if perc:
        label = "{:.1f}%".format(
            100 * p.get_height() / total
        )  # percentage of each class of the category
    else:
        label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

    x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
    y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

    plt.annotate(
        label,
        (x, y),
        ha="center",
        va="center",
        size=12,
        xytext=(0, 5),
        textcoords="offset points",
    )  # annotate the percentage

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target, rotation=90, sort_columns=True):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    rotation: rotation angle for x-axis labels (default is 90)
    sort_columns: whether to sort columns by values in the predictor/x-axis (default is True)
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]

    # make crosstab showing counts and percents of predictor to target
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True, margins_name="Total")
    tab1_percent = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True, margins_name="Total", normalize="index") * 100
    tab1_percent_str = tab1_percent.round(2).astype(str)

    # concatenate the count (n) and the %
    tab2 = (pd.concat([tab1, tab1_percent_str], axis=1, keys=['n', '%'])
      .swaplevel(axis=1)
      .sort_index(axis = 1, ascending = True)
    )
    print(tab2)
    print("-" * 120)

    # make stacked barplot
    if sort_columns:
        tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
            by=sorter, ascending=False
        )
    else:
        tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index")

    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.xticks(rotation=rotation, fontsize=15)
    plt.show()

### function to plot distributions wrt target
def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color=custom_palette[2],
        alpha=0.7,
        stat="density",
        line_kws={"color": "black"}
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color=custom_palette[3],
        alpha=0.7,
        stat="density",
        line_kws={"color": "black"}
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 0]
    )

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

def make_confusion_matrix(model,X_data_used,y_actual,labels=[1, 0]):
    '''
    model : classifier to predict values of X
    y_actual : ground truth

    '''
    y_predict = model.predict(X_data_used)
    cm=metrics.confusion_matrix( y_actual, y_predict, labels=[0, 1])
    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(cm, index = [i for i in ["Actual - No","Actual - Yes"]],
                  columns = [i for i in ['Predicted - No','Predicted - Yes']])
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                cm.flatten()]
    group_percentages = ["{0:.2%}".format(value) for value in
                         cm.flatten()/np.sum(cm)]
    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
              zip(group_counts,group_percentages)]
    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)
    plt.figure(figsize = (10,7))
    sns.heatmap(df_cm, annot=labels,fmt='')
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

There are only 34 employees that are neither full time nor annual wage workers. These employees constitute 0.1% of the data. I considered three ways to handle this data when changing all wages to an annual estimate.

  1. Treat "full_time = N" as exactly half time as an estimate.
  2. Remove the 34 employees in the full_time = N and wage =/= Year from the data set
  3. Treat the 34 employees as annual for the purposes of the wage estimate.

I opted for option 3 to simplify the treatment. These employees are mathematically treated as full-time while retaining the categorical variable 'N' for full time."

  • If we make assumptions that most US non-salaried employees work..

    • 40 hours a week
    • 52 weeks a year (accouting for 2 weeks paid leave a year in the USA for this type of employee)
    • 12 months a year
      ....then we can convert all to annual wages.

  • If these assumptions on converstion are faulty, they represent just under 10% of the data, and the categorical column of unit of wage will remain to support model building. The magnitude of the possible impact is noted.

In [26]:
# Create a function to convert wages to the yearly unit
def annualize(row):
    unit = row['unit_of_wage']
    wage = row['prevailing_wage']

    if unit == 'Hour':
        return wage * 40 * 52  # Assuming 40 hours per week and 52 weeks per year
    elif unit == 'Week':
        return wage * 52  # Assuming 52 weeks per year
    elif unit == 'Month':
        return wage * 12  # Assuming 12 months per year
    else:
        return wage  # If already in yearly unit or unknown unit, return as is

# Apply the function to create a new column 'yearly_wage'
data['yearly_wage'] = data.apply(annualize, axis=1)
data = data.drop('prevailing_wage', axis = 1)

Encoding and Data Types¶

The selected variables for Label Encoding were specifically chosen due to their ordinal nature. Conversely, the decision to use One-Hot Encoding for two variables was based on the absence of a clear ranking between their categories. Notably, the numeric data was left unbinned for this model run, enabling the decision trees to handle the possible creations of bins.

  • Label Encoding Steps -

    • education_of_employee encoded as 1-4 from High School to Doctoral
    • has_job_experice encoded as 1 for Yes and 0 for No
    • requires_job_training endoded as as 1 for Yes and 0 for No
    • unit_of_wage encoded as 1-4 from Hour to Year
    • full_time_position endoded as as 1 for Yes and 0 for No
    • case_status endocded as 1 for Certified and 0 for Denied

  • One-Hot Encoding -

    • continent creating dummy variables. Chosing to specifically drop the Asia category so that we can interpret the coefficients for the other continents in refrence to Asia. The coefficients essentially represent deviations from the largest category.
    • region_of_employement creating dummy variables. The largest category is Northeast and specifically dropped.

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criteria¶

Restatment of Purpose: In order to make the visa approval process more effiecient, recommend a suitable profile for applicants for both xases: should be certified and should be denied.

Error Types

  • Type 1 - 'false positive' - model predicts visa application will get certified, but in reality it should be denied. This results in the visa applicant taking a job that otherwise policy wants a US citizen to fill. This contributes to US unemployment and can contribute to "brain drain".
  • Type 2 - 'false negative' - model predicts visa application will be denied, but should be certified. This results in the company struggling to fill the role and grow their business and thus the US economy.

Model Criterion

  • Both types of errors would result in lower performance metrics for the OFLC
  • The F1 Score will be the strongest metric for evaluation, minimizing both types of errors equally
  • Balanced class weights will help build strong models

# Choose the type of classifier.
dtree_tuned = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=1)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    'max_depth': list(np.arange(2,20)) + [None],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 3, 5, 7, 10],
    'max_leaf_nodes' : [2, 3, 5, 10, 15] + [None],
    'min_impurity_decrease': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 0.0]
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(dtree_tuned, parameters, scoring=scorer,cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
dtree_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
dtree_tuned.fit(X_train, y_train)

|   |   |   |   |--- full_time_position <= 0.50
|   |   |   |   |   |--- class: 1
|   |   |   |   |--- full_time_position >  0.50
|   |   |   |   |   |--- class: 1

With no esmemble techniques and just a basic hyperparamets, we have our first model of the notebook. This model rates education and job experience as the highest relative imporance - which we see showing up multple times in the first 3 layers of the tree. On the test data, this model had an F1 score of .82037. Hopefully goes up from here!

Iterate through Preparation of Data for Modeling¶

My computer began to time out on the AdaBoost Classifier, which means I was unable to continue. Thus, I will backtrack to here and make some adjustments. Since I reference the original Decision Tree Model for its relevancy data, I will make a second version after this data preparation.

The two adjustments I want to try are:

  1. Eliminate a few features that do not appear to be relevant.
  2. Create small random data sets to grid search on, then use those parameters when fitting the the original data to the model.

During the EDA we saw that many of the features were equally represented in the data set. Further, at the point I was tuning the AdaBoost model, the Single Decision Tree still had the largest F1 value. The results of that model produce a relative importance list. Here is a re-print of those

# Choose the type of classifier.
xgb_tuned = XGBClassifier(random_state=1, eval_metric="logloss")

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {
    "n_estimators": np.arange(150, 250, 50),
    "scale_pos_weight": [1, 2],
    "subsample": [0.9, 1],
    "learning_rate": np.arange(0.1, 0.21, 0.1),
    "gamma": [3, 5],
    "colsample_bytree": [0.8, 0.9],
    "colsample_bylevel": [ 0.9, 1],
}

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
acc_scorer = metrics.make_scorer(metrics.f1_score)

# Run the grid search
grid_obj = GridSearchCV(xgb_tuned, parameters,scoring=acc_scorer,cv=5)
grid_obj = grid_obj.fit(X_sample_encoded, y_sample)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
xgb_tuned = grid_obj.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data.
xgb_tuned.fit(X_train_red_encoded, y_train_red)

This model has an F1 of 0.82183 - meaning there is a decent balance between Precision (measure of correctness of positive predictions) and Recall (measure of ability to correctly predict positive true labels). The model is nearly twice as good at avoiding false negatives than it is at avoiding false positives.

However, for an average day to day triage decision makeing, the first decision tree is certainly a simpler model with barly a reduction of F1.

Taking a little time with a graphic designer (or otherwise not Python) could really make this a tool in every team huddle. Lets take a look at that tree again.

In [173]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
out = tree.plot_tree(
    dtree_tuned,
    feature_names=feature_names,
    filled=True,
    fontsize=9,
    node_ids=False,
    class_names=None,
)
plt.show()

Quickly cleaning this up visually would make a strong tool for decision makers as they traige incoming applications. There are two observations worth pointing out:

  1. The one orange block on the right side of the tree reveals a pattern (or possibly a bias?) in the system - that box represents applicants with a Bachelors Degree and Job Experience, but is applying for an hourly wage. The system has the lowest rates of certification for Hourly regardless of any other feature. This observation could raise questions about potential biases in the system related to wage types and certification outcomes.

  2. The tree has several levels that interact with both Education Level and Job Experience; a candidate who has both is a strong certification indicator.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

Areas for Further Study

  • There seemed to be two useful data types not available in this data set: the sector of industry that the job would be in, and the relative level of the role (entry level, mid-career, senior, executive). Given that there were many features that held little preictive power, I wonder if there are patterns still to be found.
  • Another point of interest to me is the marital status of applicants.

Faciliation of Via Approvals

Here are a few suggestions for streamlining the process as applications continue to increase:

  • False Positives are more likely using this model than False Negatives. While denying a company and a applicant the opportunity to work in the USA, the performance metric that determins OFLC funding is the concept of "getting Americans back to work". In employing the model - the False Positives are the greater priority because there are more of them to find.

  • Allowing staff members to become their own subject matter experts may increase the efficiecy. For example,

    • A team could specialize in hourly applications from appliations with work experience and education to see if the denial rate is legitamate or a bias of the system.
    • Another team could specialize in working with the higher degree (Masters, Doctorate) holders of Africa and likely the Middle East (since I would guess they were included either in Europe or Asia depending on geography).
    • A hypothesis I have is that their could also be industry based specialists, or fresh graduates of bachelors programs specialists.

Profile of Certification

Candidates that have at least three of the following:

  • Education of at least a Bachelor's
  • Has Job Experience
  • Job is Full time or Annual Salary

  • From either Europe or Asia

    This can be essentially a coversheet or rubric for incoming application; if they have 3 or 4 of the above bullets they are lower risk false positives.

Profiles of Denial

Candidats that have at least 3 of the following:

  • High School Educated
  • Hourly Role
  • From South America
  • No Job Experience
